receptor tyrosine kinase.  The Company is also conducting Phase 1 clinical testing with ARQ 621, designed to inhibit the Eg5 kinesin motor protein.  The Company's pre-clinical pipeline includes a compound designed to inhibit the B-RAF kinase.  ArQule's current discovery efforts, which are based on the ArQule Kinase Inhibitor Platform (AKIP), are focused on the identification of novel kinase inhibitors that are potent, selective and do not compete with ATP (adenosine triphosphate) for binding to the kinase.  These include a series of small molecule inhibitors of fibroblast growth factor receptor (FGFR).
 
